"Bard E., Raisbeck G., Yiou F., Jouzel J.","Solar irradiance during the last 1200 years based on cosmogenic nuclides",2000,"Tellus, Series B: Chemical and Physical Meteorology","52","3",,"985","992",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033929083&partnerID=40&md5=51429bf47d9e34ed08dee395c140668b","CEREGE, Université d'Aix-Marseille, Europôle de l'Arbois, BP 80, 13545 Aix-en-Provence Cedex 4, France; Ctr. Spectrometrie Nucl. S., IN2P3-CNRS, 91405 Orsay, France; Lab. Sci. Climat de l'Environnement, CEA-CNRS, Orme des Merisiers, 91191 Gif-sur-Yvette cdx, France","Bard, E., CEREGE, Université d'Aix-Marseille, Europôle de l'Arbois, BP 80, 13545 Aix-en-Provence Cedex 4, France; Raisbeck, G., Ctr. Spectrometrie Nucl. S., IN2P3-CNRS, 91405 Orsay, France; Yiou, F., Ctr. Spectrometrie Nucl. S., IN2P3-CNRS, 91405 Orsay, France; Jouzel, J., Lab. Sci. Climat de l'Environnement, CEA-CNRS, Orme des Merisiers, 91191 Gif-sur-Yvette cdx, France","Based on a quantitative study of the common fluctuations of 14C and 10Be production rates, we have derived a time series of the solar magnetic variability over the last 1200 years. This record is converted into irradiance variations by linear scaling based on previous studies of sun-like stars and of the sun's behavior over the last few centuries. The new solar irradiance record exhibits low values during the well-known solar minima centered at about 1900, 1810 (Dalton) and 1690 AD (Maunder). Further back in time, a rather long period between 1450 and 1750 AD is characterized by low irradiance values. A shorter period is centered at about 1200 AD, with irradiance slightly higher or similar to present day values. It is tempting to correlate these periods with the so-called 'little ice age' and 'medieval warm period', respectively. An accurate quantification of the climatic impact of this new irradiance record requires the use of coupled atmosphere-ocean general circulation models (GCMs). Nevertheless, our record is already compatible with a global cooling of about 0.5-1°C during the 'little ice age', and with a general cooling trend during the past millenium followed by global warming during the 20th century (Mann et al., 1999).",,"cosmogenic radionuclide; irradiance; solar radiation",,,,,,"Baliunas, S., Jastrow, R., Evidence for long-term brightness changes of solar-type stars (1990) Nature, 348, pp. 520-522; Bard, E., Nuclide production by cosmic rays during the Last Ice Age (1997) Science, 277, pp. 532-533; Bard, E., Geochemical and geophysical implications of the radiocarbon calibration (1998) Geochimica Cosmochimica Acta, 62, pp. 2025-2038; Bard, E., Raisbeck, G., Yiou, F., Jouzel, J., Solar modulation of cosmogenic nuclide production over the last millenium: Comparison between 14C and 10Be records (1997) Earth Planet. Sci. Lett., 150, pp. 453-462; Beer, J., Tobias, A., Weiss, B., (1998) Solar Physics, 181, pp. 237-249; Bradley, R.S., Jones, P.D., ""Little Ice Age"" summer temperature variations: Their nature and relevance to recent global warming trends (1993) The Holocene, 3, pp. 367-376; Beer, J., Siegenthaler, U., Bonani, G., Finkel, R.C., Oeschger, H., Suter, M., Wölfli, W., Information on past solar activity and geomagnetism from 10Be in the Camp Century ice core (1988) Nature, 331, pp. 675-679; Beer, J., Blinov, A., Bonani, G., Finkel, R.C., Hofmann, H.J., Lelmann, B., Oeschger, H., Wölfli, W., Use of 10Be in polar ice to trace the 11-year cycle of solar activity (1990) Nature, 347, pp. 164-166; Cliver, E.W., Boriakoff, V., Feynman, J., Solar variability and climate change: Geomagnetic and aa index and global surface temperature (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett., 25, pp. 1035-1038; Crowley, T.J., Kim, K.-Y., Comparison of proxy records of climate change and solar forcing (1996) Geophys. Res. Lett., 23, pp. 359-362; Cubash, U., Voss, R., Hegerl, G.C., Waszkewitz, J., Crowley, T.J., Simulation of the influence of solar radiation variations on the global climate with an ocean-atmosph